<subSubSection id="DDFB654FEF49FFF4FF69FD32FDBAFD27" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="955E36C4EF49FFF4FF69FD32FDBAFD27" blockId="6.[178,1085,711,764]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">Etymology: The specific epithet (Latin, adjective) alludes to the bisinuate ventral process of the aedeagus in lateral view.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DDFB654FEF49FFF5FF69FCFEFBD5FA86" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="456" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" type="description">
<paragraph id="955E36C4EF49FFF4FF69FCFEFBE5FC87" blockId="6.[178,1085,779,860]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">
Description: Body length 
<quantity id="52199B21EF49FFF4FDC6FCFEFD6DFCFA" box="[541,663,779,801]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.9" metricValueMax="6.1" metricValueMin="5.7" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" unit="mm" value="5.9" valueMax="6.1" valueMin="5.7">5.7-6.1 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 
<quantity id="52199B21EF49FFF4FCB1FCFEFC19FCFA" box="[874,995,779,801]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.25" metricValueMax="3.3" metricValueMin="3.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="455" unit="mm" value="3.25" valueMax="3.3" valueMin="3.2">3.2-3.3 mm</quantity>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="0DDA2A41EF49FFF4FF32FCDCFECFFCE4" box="[233,309,809,831]" captionStart="Figs 15-19" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1160,1180]" captionTargetBox="[182,1033,220,1136]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[178,1082,212,1141]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 15-19: Rugilus bisinuosus nov.sp.: (15) habitus; (16) forebody; (17) male sternite VII; (18) male sternite VIII; (19) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 17-18: 0.5 mm; 19: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305045/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
. Coloration: body blackish; elytra with weak bronze hue; legs and antennae reddish, with the apical portions of the femora and antennomere I somewhat infuscate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="955E36C4EF49FFF4FF69FC9EFD4AFBEA" blockId="6.[178,1086,875,1073]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">
Head (
<figureCitation id="0DDA2A41EF49FFF4FF23FC9EFEBEFC5A" box="[248,324,875,897]" captionStart="Figs 15-19" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1160,1180]" captionTargetBox="[182,1033,220,1136]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[178,1082,212,1141]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 15-19: Rugilus bisinuosus nov.sp.: (15) habitus; (16) forebody; (17) male sternite VII; (18) male sternite VIII; (19) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 17-18: 0.5 mm; 19: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305045/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) 1.04-1.07 times as broad as long, broadest across eyes; margins behind eyes smoothly curving towards posterior constriction in dorsal view, posterior angles obsolete; punctation moderately coarse, umbilicate, largely longitudinally confluent, and very dense; interstices reduced to very narrow ridges. Eyes large and strongly convex, approximately 0.8-0.9 times as long as distance from posterior margin of eyes to posterior constriction. Anterior margin of labrum with two pronounced, basally fused teeth on either side of the narrow median incision.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="955E36C4EF49FFF4FF69FBB4FD64FB4A" blockId="6.[178,1085,1088,1169]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="0DDA2A41EF49FFF4FEF0FBB5FE81FB8D" box="[299,379,1088,1110]" captionStart="Figs 15-19" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1160,1180]" captionTargetBox="[182,1033,220,1136]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[178,1082,212,1141]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 15-19: Rugilus bisinuosus nov.sp.: (15) habitus; (16) forebody; (17) male sternite VII; (18) male sternite VIII; (19) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 17-18: 0.5 mm; 19: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305045/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) weakly oblong, approximately 1.1 times as long as broad and approximately 0.75 times as wide as head; midline with short impunctate, glossy band in posterior half; punctation similar to that of head.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="955E36C4EF49FFF4FF69FB55FECAFAD5" blockId="6.[178,1085,1184,1294]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="0DDA2A41EF49FFF4FED9FB55FEB5FB6D" box="[258,335,1184,1206]" captionStart="Figs 15-19" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1160,1180]" captionTargetBox="[182,1033,220,1136]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[178,1082,212,1141]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 15-19: Rugilus bisinuosus nov.sp.: (15) habitus; (16) forebody; (17) male sternite VII; (18) male sternite VIII; (19) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 17-18: 0.5 mm; 19: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305045/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) short, approximately 0.75 times as long as pronotum; humeral angles practically obsolete; punctation dense; interstices glossy. Hind wings completely reduced. Legs long and slender; metatarsomere I slightly longer than the combined length of II and III.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="955E36C4EF49FFF4FF69FAE8FDEEFA73" blockId="6.[178,1086,1309,1448]" pageId="6" pageNumber="455">Abdomen 1.15-1.20 times as broad as elytra; tergites III-VI with shallow impressions anteriorly, these impressions with moderately coarse and dense punctation; punctation of remaining tergal surfaces fine and moderately dense; interstices of tergites III-VI with very shallow, those of tergite V with more distinct microreticulation; posterior margin of tergite VII without palisade fringe.</paragraph>
<caption id="C19E664CEF48FFF5FF69FB7DFF04FB11" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305045" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5305045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305045/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" startId="7.[178,218,1160,1180]" targetBox="[182,1033,220,1136]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph id="955E36C4EF48FFF5FF69FB7DFF04FB11" blockId="7.[178,1086,1160,1226]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">
<emphasis id="A795EAD6EF48FFF5FF69FB7DFEE2FB47" bold="true" box="[178,280,1160,1180]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">Figs 15-19</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName id="52E14D47EF48FFF5FEFCFB7DFE2FFB47" authority="Assing, 2014" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2014" box="[295,469,1160,1180]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bisinuosus" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis id="A795EAD6EF48FFF5FEFCFB7DFE2FFB47" box="[295,469,1160,1180]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">Rugilus bisinuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="BCA657ADEF48FFF5FE06FB7DFDD9FB47" box="[477,547,1160,1180]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
: (
<emphasis id="A795EAD6EF48FFF5FDEEFB7DFDB6FB47" bold="true" box="[565,588,1160,1180]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">15</emphasis>
) habitus; (
<emphasis id="A795EAD6EF48FFF5FD6FFB7DFD31FB47" bold="true" box="[692,715,1160,1180]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">16</emphasis>
) forebody; (
<emphasis id="A795EAD6EF48FFF5FC98FB7DFCA0FB47" bold="true" box="[835,858,1160,1180]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">17</emphasis>
) male sternite VII; (
<emphasis id="A795EAD6EF48FFF5FBC4FB7DFBCCFB47" bold="true" box="[1055,1078,1160,1180]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">18</emphasis>
) male sternite VIII; (
<emphasis id="A795EAD6EF48FFF5FEB6FB6AFE7EFB68" bold="true" box="[365,388,1183,1203]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">19</emphasis>
) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 17-18: 0.5 mm; 19: 0.2 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="955E36C4EF48FFF5FF1CFB2DFBD5FA86" blockId="7.[178,1085,1239,1373]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">
: sternite VII (
<figureCitation id="0DDA2A41EF48FFF5FE87FB22FE5DFB36" box="[348,423,1239,1261]" captionStart="Figs 15-19" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1160,1180]" captionTargetBox="[182,1033,220,1136]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[178,1082,212,1141]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 15-19: Rugilus bisinuosus nov.sp.: (15) habitus; (16) forebody; (17) male sternite VII; (18) male sternite VIII; (19) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 17-18: 0.5 mm; 19: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305045/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) strongly transverse and with unmodified pubescence, posterior margin with distinct median excision; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="0DDA2A41EF48FFF5FD12FB06FCE9FAD2" box="[713,787,1267,1289]" captionStart="Figs 15-19" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1160,1180]" captionTargetBox="[182,1033,220,1136]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[178,1082,212,1141]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 15-19: Rugilus bisinuosus nov.sp.: (15) habitus; (16) forebody; (17) male sternite VII; (18) male sternite VIII; (19) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 17-18: 0.5 mm; 19: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305045/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) weakly transverse, approximately 1.05 times as broad as long, posterior excision narrowly V-shaped, approximately 0.3 times as deep as length of sternite; aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="0DDA2A41EF48FFF5FD60FADEFCFDFA9A" box="[699,775,1323,1345]" captionStart="Figs 15-19" captionStartId="7.[178,218,1160,1180]" captionTargetBox="[182,1033,220,1136]" captionTargetId="figure-2@7.[178,1082,212,1141]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 15-19: Rugilus bisinuosus nov.sp.: (15) habitus; (16) forebody; (17) male sternite VII; (18) male sternite VIII; (19) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 15-16: 1.0 mm; 17-18: 0.5 mm; 19: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305045/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) approximately 
<quantity id="52199B21EF48FFF5FC69FADEFBFBFA9A" box="[946,1025,1323,1345]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" unit="mm" value="1.1">1.1 mm</quantity>
long; ventral process conspicuously slender, bisinuate in lateral view, and apically very acute.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DDFB654FEF48FFF5FF69FA9EFEF4F9F2" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="955E36C4EF48FFF5FF69FA9EFEF4F9F2" blockId="7.[178,1086,1387,1577]" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">
Comparative notes: 
<taxonomicName id="52E14D47EF48FFF5FDCAFA9EFD2BFA5A" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2014" box="[529,721,1387,1409]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bisinuosus">
<emphasis id="A795EAD6EF48FFF5FDCAFA9EFD2BFA5A" box="[529,721,1387,1409]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">Rugilus bisinuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized particularly by the distinctive shape of the morphology of the ventral process of the aedeagus and by the shape of the male sternite VII. It is additionally distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="52E14D47EF48FFF5FCB0FA51FBEBFA62" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2012" box="[875,1041,1443,1465]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="manasluensis">
<emphasis id="A795EAD6EF48FFF5FCB0FA51FBEBFA62" box="[875,1041,1443,1465]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">R. manasluensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="52E14D47EF48FFF5FF69FA35FED0FA0E" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2014" box="[178,298,1471,1493]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="456" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schmidti">
<emphasis id="A795EAD6EF48FFF5FF69FA35FED0FA0E" box="[178,298,1471,1493]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="456">R. schmidti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the only other locally endemic consubgeners known from the Manaslu range, by the less oblong pronotum, the strongly confluent punctation of the head and pronotum, and by the less transverse male sternite VIII with a much narrower posterior excision.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DDFB654FEF47FFFAFF69FF2FFD35FE93" pageId="8" pageNumber="457" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="955E36C4EF47FFFAFF69FF2FFD35FE93" blockId="8.[178,1085,218,328]" pageId="8" pageNumber="457">
Distribution and natural history: The 
<typeStatus id="4A5A8866EF47FFFAFCECFF2EFC99FF2B" box="[823,867,219,240]" pageId="8" pageNumber="457">type</typeStatus>
locality is situated in the southeastern Manaslu range at an altitude of 
<quantity id="52199B21EF47FFFAFD45FF0DFCD2FED6" box="[670,808,248,270]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.65" metricValueMax="2.8" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="457" unit="m" value="2650.0" valueMax="2800.0" valueMin="2500.0">2500-2800 m</quantity>
. It can be inferred from the restricted distributions of other micropterous consubgeners known from 
<collectingCountry id="EDF67654EF47FFFAFC6BFEE0FC16FEF0" box="[944,1004,277,299]" name="Nepal" pageId="8" pageNumber="457">Nepal</collectingCountry>
that 
<taxonomicName id="52E14D47EF47FFFAFBFCFEE3FEE7FE93" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2014" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Rugilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="457" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bisinuosus">
<emphasis id="A795EAD6EF47FFFAFBFCFEE3FEE7FE93" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="457">R. bisinuosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably locally endemic in this region.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
